content:
Liked it too.
Perhaps it could have used more types (date, decimal, ...), but it's already funny like that.
After several editions, the requirement is tougher than before, deserves a medium difficulty.

The puzzle is difficult or easy is not my concern. It has to be interesting. 
I felt it interesting at the first glance because it could be an opportunity to try dynamic comparator for sorting (sorting string and number in different columns, on demand, in different test cases). But it turned out that it is not the case, and is disappointing. Could you improve it, and possibly enhance your code?

Have a remaining problem. Now coders have to guess what datatype it is in each column. It can be a string or a number. (Is there a third type, like a datetime?) Sorting a string is by alphanumeric ordering; sorting a number is by the value in the number. If you do not explicitly tell coders what datatype it is, the guessing can be wrong. For example, a column full of [0..9] looks like a number sorting, but it can also be a string or date sorting. Who knows?
You need to provide the data type, possibly by adding a line below your Line1:

+age-name
number,string

The ordering is not precisely given. 
Clearly NOT a medium puzzle (maybe an easy one)

Nice.

Test cases could be a bit too week.
The statement made an example +prop1-prop2+prop3, but test cases are containing at most 2 properties.

You can make longer sorting list and add in constraints the max sorting prop
Hey ! Indeed, thanks. On my way :)

I'll try to detail the goal.
I changed the difficulty level btw.

That's the reason all 'ages' in the inputs are > 10, because 8 > 18 with a string comparison..
That's not a bad idea, but in real life you know on wich type you're sorting, don't have to guess it. Maybe this can be interesting but we need to limit the types to be string | int, or maybe i can explain in the ordering that only alpha sorting should be used (to keep this puzzle an easy one..) which is better ?
Thank you for your constructive help and tips, are you sure that it deserves medium ?
Looks much better than it was!

if you are basing on a particular data range (9<x<100) to make the sorting correct, that's very bad, seriously bad. First, it was not explained clearly. Second, even if it was explained it violates the common sense that numbers should have a much wider range than your self-limited range assumption. A useful program should not crash just because the age of a person is 100 or above.

For sure ! Misunderstanding.. ( my approximative english maybe.. ) my intention was to do only alphanumeric ordering, an the 'age' property should be treated like the others, just to keep the puzzle as simple as possible. If you think that value sorting is compliant maybe i can do it but the puzzle should be a bit more difficult with types in input.
it makes way more sense now, thanks !
